<subsection xml:id="subsec-expressing-probability-outcomes-in-fractions-in-different-situations">
    <title>Expressing probability outcomes in fractions in different situations</title>
    <p>
        Expressing probability outcomes in fractions means representing the likelihood of an event happening as a fraction, where the numerator represents the number of desired outcomes and the denominator represents the total number of possible outcomes.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key points about expressing probability as fractions:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Structure: A probability fraction is written as "favorable outcomes / total possible outcomes". 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Interpretation: The larger the numerator, the higher the probability of the desired event happening. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Range: Probabilities expressed as fractions always fall between 0 (impossible event) and 1 (certain event). 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
